commit_message:
matchmaker_redis compatibility with redis-py 2.4

From the redis documentation: "In addition to the changes above,
the Redis class, a subclass of StrictRedis, overrides several other
commands to provide backwards compatibility with older versions
of redis-py"

Change-Id: I76ca0d9660b086dfed74733f63450fecb89decb7
Closes-Bug: 1245447

So, the way those tests are structured, the list() method shouldn't ever be called.  The fact that it is indicates that something is wrong with how the UUID is interpreted under Python 3.3.  (You should get the same basic error under Python 2.7 if list() is called; the fact that you aren't suggests that the problem is with the UUID interpretation in Python 3.3.)

I would suggest starting by looking at the implementation of the UUID check: compare it to the current code in oslo-incubator and see if we need a synchronization, for instance.  I'll try to take a closer look myself at some later point, but I'm afraid I have some other priorities that may keep me from doing so today…"}, {'account_id': 8106, 'date': '2013-11-07 23:59:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
nova security-group-* should support uuid as input

If we installed neutron, the security-group request will be handled
by neutron, however neutron is using uuid as key for security-group,
nova uses an int value as key, for current novaclient, it only
support the security-group which key is int, so will raise exception
for uuid input.

Change-Id: Ia230d12a1b4905434024b1a5129aa91cff7e6a5b
Closes-Bug: #1247728

commit_message:
Updates .gitignore

To ignore swap files from getting into repository
currently the implemented ignore is *.swp
however vim adds more swap files if these files exists,
so improving this with *.sw?

Change-Id: Ic3e09f8cf0be35c98d89d862d40121a09c7b2498
Closes-Bug: #1255876

commit_message:
Deprecates V2 controllers

The revocation_list controller method's code was copied from the v2
controller to the v3 controller.  This allows us to cleanly deprecate
the v2 API without impacting the v3 API.

Closes-Bug:#1222696
Change-Id: I0ca7a091a50007c07dfe6942b2653c617ca98e70

messages:
[{'account_id': 7714, 'date': '2013-11-15 22:02:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2013-11-17 18:01:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (3 inline comments)

Overall looks pretty good. As said in the dependent patch, I think calling it just 'metadata' would be my preferred option.

Some additional general thoughts: For many of the examples in the hot_spec my gut feeling is that those could be things we want to "standardize" in the spec, i.e. really prescribe the name and use of the metadata element to ensure appropriate display in all UIs that deal with HOT templates.
I understand that this is pragmatic way to get started, so we could be fine with packing this all in metadata without further specification, but wanted to raise the point for consideration.

Some specific comments inlne.'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2013-11-18 04:58:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(7 inline comments)

"}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-11-18 09:44:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

I'm also not sure about stack_metadata, my vote would be for "tags", with arbitrary key/value pairs, which describes the intent of the section better, IMO, and avoids yet another confusing usage of the generic "metadata" keyword.'}, {'account_id': 7714, 'date': '2013-11-18 15:17:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)

Thanks for all of the grammar help. I'll have another patch up soon.

I'll go ahead and swap out "stack_metadata" for "tags". I understand how overloaded "metadata" is so I'm fine with something related like "tags".'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2013-11-18 16:24:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

In general I would be fine with 'tags' as well. I only would like to mention that tags are generally seen as simple name-value pairs by most people, so putting complex stuff in there might look odd. Don't have a better proposal though ;-)"}, {'account_id': 7714, 'date': '2013-11-18 21:03:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 7714, 'date': '2013-11-18 21:05:16.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2013-11-18 21:05:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

New patchset patch-id matches previous patchset, but whitespace content has changed.'}, {'account_id': 7714, 'date': '2013-11-18 21:06:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I fixed all of the grammar errors that were noted and changed the name to "tags". I would also like to throw out some other possible options: "extra_data" or "reference_data".'}, {'account_id': 7896, 'date': '2013-11-18 22:28:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: (1 inline comment)

Like most of us, not thrilled with "tags" (might as well call it "stuff" ;-) ). This is template metadata, i.e. metadata in the scope of the template, so one would say "template_metadata" makes some sense, but then again it is sort of redundant because you are adding a top level attribute to a template, so it should be obvious it is a template -> metadata. Then again, we seemed to have agreed that the template version would be specified as "heat_template_version", which is just as redundant (i.e. we know it is in the scope of Heat and template). Perhaps that should've been "format_version", "schema_version", "version" (this one could be mistaken with revisions of the template though, so not such a great choice), etc.

When I look at this new attribute, it seems to me that is just a generic extension mechanism which is meant to be interpreted by specific tools, so why not name this "extensions", and have a "sub" attribute "name:" which hints as to who is going to consume these values? Is possible I did not interpret this correctly, but this is how I read into it.

Thanks'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-18 22:36:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

commit_message:
Updates HOT spec and guide for stack_metadata

This commit adds documentation to the HOT specification describing
the proposed new section of the HOT syntax, stack_metadata. It
describes a few of the proposed use-cases for this section and
updates the HOT guide.

Implements: blueprint update-stack-metadata-spec
Change-Id: I95428664538255a22929d0b5121e3cfc435f05d8

Serving keystone from a wsgi container is recommended for production
setups. SSL is enabled by default.

See the following URLs for explanations:
    http://adam.younglogic.com/2012/03/keystone-should-move-to-apache-httpd/
    https://etherpad.openstack.org/havana-keystone-performance

Documentation in manifests/wsgi/apache.pp

Apache can be configured as a drop in replacement for keystone (using
    ports 5000 & 35357) or with paths using the standard SSL port. See
examples in examples/apache_*.pp

- Also change some 'real_' prefix into '_real' suffix to respect the
coding guide.
- Added the '--insecure' option to keystone client in the provider to
allow using self-signed certificates.
- Fixed parsing the ssl/enable value in the provider.

There is no integer verification done in the manifests
and to get around a bug in rspec, which has been fixed
in https://github.com/rodjek/rspec-puppet/pull/107,
certain parameters that should be integer are treated as
strings

files/httpd/keystone.py updated with lastest from keystone git repo

Change-Id: Ide8c090d105c1ea75a14939f5e8ddb7d24ca3f1c

commit_message:
Enable serving keystone from apache mod_wsgi

Serving keystone from a wsgi container is recommended for production
setups. SSL is enabled by default.

See the following URLs for explanations:
    http://adam.younglogic.com/2012/03/keystone-should-move-to-apache-httpd/
    https://etherpad.openstack.org/havana-keystone-performance

Documentation in manifests/wsgi/apache.pp

Apache can be configured as a drop in replacement for keystone (using
    ports 5000 & 35357) or with paths using the standard SSL port. See
examples in examples/apache_*.pp

- Also change some 'real_' prefix into '_real' suffix to respect the
coding guide.
- Added the '--insecure' option to keystone client in the provider to
allow using self-signed certificates.
- Fixed parsing the ssl/enable value in the provider.

There is no integer verification done in the manifests
and to get around a bug in rspec, which has been fixed
in https://github.com/rodjek/rspec-puppet/pull/107,
certain parameters that should be integer are treated as
strings

files/httpd/keystone.py updated with lastest from keystone git repo

Change-Id: Ide8c090d105c1ea75a14939f5e8ddb7d24ca3f1c

commit_message:
Comply with new hacking 0.8 release

Fixes a couple of small issues to pass all PEP8 tests in
the new hacking release

H235  assert_ is deprecated, use assertTrue
H231  Python 3.x incompatible 'except x,y:' construct
H234  assertEquals is deprecated, use assertEqual
H301  one import per line
H302  import only modules
H233  Python 3.x incompatible use of print operator

Change-Id: I0e5e74944e2b034b223ada1b3d0be66f2a9a5722

commit_message:
Moved keystone db sync to its own class

This will decouple allowing for additions, like the apache wsgi
patch, so it can be included or triggered elsewhere.

Original author is François Charlier<francois.charlier@enovance.com>

Change-Id: I9ae544d58034ca30ddb0a4c616ff794ccd432d7f

commit_message:
Remove authutils

As discussed during the Icehouse summit, this library is not used
anymore by any project. Let's get rid of it.

Reference:
  https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/icehouse-oslo-status

subject: WIP: make merge.py installable as a package using pbr
messages:
[{'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-29 13:16:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- gate-noop http://logs.openstack.org/76/59176/1/check/gate-noop/084b154 : SUCCESS in 0s
'}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2013-11-29 13:19:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sorry for the mess, I abandoned the original review @ c/58823/ so I could make this dependent on Ia6b6416fe10358d23f2b120283eecaf4c1178cfd

Mark's original comments, with my response after:

Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(4 inline comments)

I think this will work out fine, thanks Marios

Perhaps try leaving all the templates in the toplevel directory and not include them in the python package. Moving them will mean updating devtest, etc. and the goal isn't to package them, it's to package merge.py

Could we call the python package tripleo-heat-merge or something? i.e. the important thing we're packaging is the merging code, not the templates.

I'm suggesting the tripleo prefix to recognize this isn't generally useful and we want it to go away in time.

==============================

Mark, thanks again. I renamed the package and script. The reason I moved the templates into the /templates directory is because I couldn't get pbr to play with *.yaml as a glob... i mean:

data_files=*.yaml

just _wouldn't_ work. IMO it is preferable to move them into a templates directory (since for some reason, templates/* _does_ work), rather than have to enumerate them individually, which wouldn't scale well."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-12-01 21:25:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

So this change appears to several distinct things such as moving templates around, making the package installable etc. Please do one thing per changeset. In particular, also be aware of the impact on devtest with these changes - you'll need changesets up there to deal with both the new and old structure before this is mergable."}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-12-02 07:33:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Marios - it's really best to avoid changing Change-Ids like this and losing the original context; could you restore I587fa7a826f93f89e8e5c266af7f5765438fe738 then use 'git commit --amend' to change the Change-Id back to I587fa7a826f93f89e8e5c266af7f5765438fe738 and re-push?"}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2013-12-03 13:32:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Mark: sure will do, sorry still learning the 'done things' ;) - anyhow the reason this was done has gone since Ia6b6416fe10358d23f2b120283eecaf4c1178cfd has now landed"}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2013-12-03 13:36:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

abandoning for I587fa7a826f93f89e8e5c266af7f5765438fe738 - merge.py being invokable is no longer a dependency'}]

commit_message:
Simplify common base exception prototype

It seems there's no gain in trying to be smarter and different from the
base Python Exception, so let's remove our custom code to be more
compatible and friendly with all Python versions.

Change-Id: I259783ef1f77c6661ea7dc2325605c8d6290b898

commit_message:
Fix a bug some optional field in LBaaS are mandatory

* VIP connection_limit
* Pool Member weight

Closes-Bug: #1241209
Closes-Bug: #1241004

The change of create_stubs in openstack_dashboard/test/helpers.py
is cherry-picked from commit fa3a039d0585c8c995504c09657070af4025305f.
It allows us to create_stubs decorator for sub methods with arguments.

Change-Id: I337215938645f6785393925f201567f2143d133e
(cherry picked from commit c9f4e27aa5c60bc997e70b4982856bbf4a23372b)

commit_message:
Use assertEqual instead of assertEquals in unit tests

The method assertEquals has been deprecated since python 2.7.
http://docs.python.org/2/library/unittest.html#deprecated-aliases
Also in Python 3, a deprecated warning is raised when using assertEquals
therefore we should use assertEqual instead.

Change-Id: I16f5201978499d9935dcf01efc0241dee9061b90
Closes-Bug: #1256738

commit_message:
Use assertNotEqual instead of assertNotEquals in unit tests

The method assertNotEquals has been deprecated.
In Python 3, a deprecated warning is raised when using assertNotEquals
therefore we should use assertNotEqual instead.

Change-Id: Iba8dcfdcfb8932f1fe1aa36e57a8ea7dc5d7627a
Closes-Bug: #1256737

commit_message:
Remaining TODO in shell.py

This commix updates the environment variables as it is indicated in the TODO which has been removed.
This change is done in order to use the environment variables with OS_ instead the old ones such as OS_SERVICE_TOKEN and OS_SERVICE_ENDPOINT.

Closes-Bug: #1256352

commit_message:
Properly reconnect subscribing clients when QPID broker restarts

When the QPID broker is restarted (or fails over), subscribed clients
will attempt to re-establish their connections.  In the case of fanout
subscriptions, this reconnection functionality is broken. For version
1 topologies, the clients attempt to reconnect twice to the same
exclusive address - which is illegal.  In the case of version 2
topologies, the address parsing is broken and an illegal address is
created on reconnect.  This fix avoids the problem by removing the
special-case reconnect code that manages UUID addresses; it is
unnecessary as the QPID broker will generate unique queue names
automatically when the clients reconnect.

Closes-bug: #1251757
Co-authored-by: Mark McLoughlin <markmc@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I6051fb503663bb8c7c5468db6bcde10f6cf1b318

commit_message:
Drop dependency on processutils from oslo db code

We should remove processutils module usage from common db code
before we split oslo.db from oslo-incubator into a separate library
because common processutils module uses common log module (so,
registers a few oslo.config options) and eventlet.

We use processutils module only as commands module replacement, so
we can use subprocess module from python standard library instead.

Related to blueprint oslo-db-lib

Change-Id: Id5ff507c9da329fa6ac58e54f8f4d0fb574ab04f

commit_message:
Fix locking in migration tests

The migration test code included an external lock with a hard-coded
relative path that breaks when run in Jenkins.  It wasn't being hit
in Oslo because it was only locking for the postgres code path,
which isn't currently tested in Oslo.

This change moves the lock so that it applies to all db types and
removes the relative path.  For the locks to work properly it was
also necessary to add the lockutils wrapper to the Oslo tox.ini.

Closes-Bug: 1255608
Change-Id: I333b833022f208e48e3b7e82e8cfad2764be5ea0

move negative tests in test_keypairs into a separate file

Converted README to .rst format

The other os-*-config projects use `.rst' format and many of our docs
do too. And we can also avoid using github flavored markedown.

subject: Run OSTF several time if it fails but less then attempts amount
messages:
[{'account_id': 8767, 'date': '2013-12-03 07:14:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 406, 'date': '2013-12-03 10:24:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Do not merge

I think we should not do tests which are like
"let's try multiple times, may be it will pass at least once... "

It must pass from the very first time by design. And, by the way, from second and third run too. I even vote for introducing such a test - run OSTF 2-3 times, and verify that all of test runs have:
a) same results
b) result is expected
If results are not same - it is one bug, and if result is wrong - another one.'}, {'account_id': 8767, 'date': '2013-12-03 11:54:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Increase Keypair name size to 255

The keypair name in horizon has a max_length of 20 characters, it seems short.
We should just match the nova data model length, and set the max_length to 255
for consistency.

Change-Id: I53e43a792da677c39127ab43831dde5f70e588d3
Closes-Bug: #1257030

commit_message:
Better @memoized decorator

This version of the @memoized decorator only keeps weak references to
the function arguments in cache, which means that it doesn't keep
objects alive forever, and that it won't fill up all available memory
eventually, as the old version would -- it only keeps cache for the
objects that are actually in use.

Honestly, I'm not actually sure that the effect is worth it, as the
level of complexity of this code is quite high. I thought I would
submit it anyways, so that we can at least have a discussion.

Change-Id: I3a4fca3aba7c52102673f7fa5d127873c71516f8
Partial-Bug: #1098047

commit_message:
Show volume quota graphs if totalVolumesUsed >= 0

commit 9bca5d3680ee21d2b92ba6766f13b5d216fc477f fixed the
volume quota display, but quotas are hidden if a project has a used
quota of 0. I don't think we should hide the quotas in this case,
as users still need to know how much quota is available, even if they
haven't used any of it yet.

Change-Id: I72c0fae1a51cafabfcde8970c94097069083dd06
Partial-Bug: #1244875

commit_message:
Remove duplicate FlavorNotFound exception handling in server create API

The v2 and v3 openstack server create APIs have duplicate handling for
the FlavorNotFound exception. This patch removes the duplicate handling
which is found in a generic catch-all block for each API.

Closes-Bug: #1256427

Change-Id: I78344cd588178c501398147f3afcd418e0744b0d

commit_message:
Return map parsed value at JsonParam.value

Currently, JsonParam returns String value as JsonParam.value.
However, SCHEMA_TYPES:MAP property doesn't support getting String value.
JsonParam have to return map value for to work properly.

Fixes bug #1256891

Change-Id: Ia4a7fcc357a4765cfd1b2e2f72fa3dff08d5b6d7

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-17 14:16:42.000000000', 'message': "Add Host Reservation Admin API

Initial release of Host Reservation Admin API by adding more methods
to the current Lease API mapped to /computehosts/ context.

The goal of this API is to be admin-only, defining CRUD methods for
adding a host to Compute, aiming to dedicate it for lease management.

As a result, the added host won't be available for booting VMs on it
unless Climate specifically picks it from a specific freepool to the
user' pcloud associated with the host reservation.

For better testing, current RPCProxy methods don't call RPC, and only
return True.

Change-Id: I58d986fe8344b9578b2f15399ec19f7649cc3035

commit_message:
Add Host Reservation Admin API

Initial release of Host Reservation Admin API by adding new classes
to the current Lease API mapped to /os-hosts/ context.

The goal of this API is to be admin-only, defining CRUD methods for
adding a host to Compute, aiming to dedicate it for lease management.

As a result, the added host won't be available for booting VMs on it
unless Climate specifically picks it from a specific freepool to the
user' pcloud associated with the host reservation.

For testing, please patch RPC methods like this :
    call = lambda *args, **kwargs: True
    cast = lambda *args, **kwargs: True

TODO :
 - Add @policy.authorize() to climate.api.oshosts.service controllers
   once review 57200 (Policy mgmt) is merged

Implements bp:host-provisioning-api

Change-Id: I58d986fe8344b9578b2f15399ec19f7649cc3035

commit_message:
Prepare dashboard for a new metadata package file structure.

New file structure allows for using same form definition file for
several services. Fields 'type', 'name' and 'description' are taken
from form definition file, as before, but now these fields should be
inferred from 'full_service_name', 'service_display_name' and
'description' fields, appropriately, from service manifest by metadata
repository.

Change-Id: Icd8b3ffbaef6432a0ba12c21d5f34d96c6b03b2e

commit_message:
Ship with etc/oslo.rootwrap instead of etc/oslo

Ship default configuration file in etc/oslo.rootwrap to encourage best
packaging practices (packagers should deploy rootwrap.conf in
/etc/oslo.rootwrap rather than /etc/oslo/rootwrap or /etc/oslo).

Also change default filters_path directory from
/etc/oslo.rootwrap/rootwrap.d to /etc/oslo.rootwrap/filters.d
as it avoids redundancy and is more self-explanatory.

Change-Id: Iadf623571283cba1886bb27a5f55c59ba66c522f

commit_message:
Adds improvements to the Swift TempURL test

Adds one extra test, to cover the Temp-URL-Key-2 header. It also adds
the possibility to skip this test by adding an entry in the config
file.

Change-Id: I084e15b9f405bf880ffd4829f57b283cbc065afa

commit_message:
Ensure proper notifications are sent when build finishes

An error condition was missing a notification, and one of the
notifications was incorrect.  Now all build failures will send a
notification and will send the correct notification based on what
occurred.

bp remove-cast-to-schedule-run-instance

Change-Id: Ibffe35da221730283b8ad3016a25dd42b5526f37

commit_message:
Catch InstanceIsLocked exception on server actions

In v3, if the server is locked, a 409 error is raised, and the error msg
is like "the server is locked". In v2 now, the 409 error is raised too. But the
error msg is like "Instance is in an invalid state for \'pause(action name)\'".
The error msg is inappropriate, two points:
1. the state is valid for pause
2. the message doesn't tell that the instance is locked

The patch fixes the ploblem, and will do as v3. See the v3 commit:
2c9fca6a3c916f3f594ddbb1a8ee8946b8ea3ac7

Change-Id: I76572e37af686a4af35c31a3ea27f7070894b88a
Closes-Bug: #1255386

commit_message:
Revert "Don't call credentials_headers() twice"

With this change, stack create fails when deferred_auth_method=password due to lack of credentials

This reverts commit a7ba3c323b16227e0ba2527f21bc89625f125234

Note some fixup in addition to the revert was required to make the
tests pass, as ShellTestToken and ShellTestStandaloneToken now require
username/password set in the fake env.

Change-Id: I703adddceae85282dc8faef92d57be573d4871d2

Hey can you give me any sight into how the tests work? They don't pass for me locally either, but they're sorta meta - I think they're doing something with doc strings?"}, {'account_id': 1994, 'date': '2013-11-20 00:53:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

In which situations should this be skipped?'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-11-20 01:29:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

from pep8:

A good rule of thumb is to limit use of bare 'except' clauses to two cases:

 * If the exception handler will be printing out or logging the traceback; at least the user will be aware that an error has occurred.
 * If the code needs to do some cleanup work, but then lets the exception propagate upwards with raise. try...finally can be a better way to handle this case.

In particular Swift has historically included lots of defensive code with the explicit goal of Pokemon exception handling - gotta catch 'em all.

You can read more on these conclusions from other Swift core dev's on the reviews referenced in my first comment, in particular Sam has (as always) made a quite lucid argument:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56712/

We had bugs resulting from people trying to enforce using a named exception when a bare except is more appropriate.  There's really no question at this point that we do not wish to apply this rule 100% of the time (although all agree it sound practice handle explicit exceptions explicitly where appropriate!).  Our option as it stands is to disable H201 for the project or maybe if I'm lucky we can land a patch like this one upstream (but with passing tests!) and require contributors to explicitly document their catch all exception handling with a noqa tag - which seems like it might be a reasonable compromise.

Speaking of which - can anyone provide some insight to how these tests are supposed to work?  I'm seeing errors in my local run that appear at least superficially unrelated and I've verified the code works functionally and seems unlikely the introduce any regression - but the test suite is totally abstract and cryptic to me?"}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-11-25 21:47:46.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-25 21:55:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

I would still prefer most cases to just catch Exception, KeyboardException, etc. directly to avoid potential pitfalls, but if projects have real cases where that is not sufficient then I'd be fine with having a #noqa option.

I added Alex Gaynor to the review for his thoughts, too."}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2013-12-02 21:36:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-12-02 21:54:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

LGTM (but I am not factoring in the reasoning behind the use of a bare except), although I would prefer to get a +1 from Doug Hellmann before landing this.'}, {'account_id': 7680, 'date': '2013-12-02 21:59:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I'm of mixed mind. I'm pretty skeptical that a bare except is every something you want, I don't think I've ever seen an exception derive BaseException but not Exception, nor do I usually want to catch SystemExit/KeyboardInterrupt usually.

On the other hand, having noqa for some things but not others seems weird.

I suppose I'm opposed, but don't feel very strongly about it (-0 if you will)."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-12-02 22:01:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

Let's go ahead. We're making software, not carving stone tablets. If Alex, or someone else, has a technical reason to revert this feature we can."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-02 22:01:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: No score

commit_message:
Add noqa support for H201 (bare except)

This'll be nice to have in high-level exception handlers that really do want
to catch *everything*

For example, Swift has some error handling code that is intended to
prevent exceptions from ever getting back to the user.  Because we
don't know what exception classes a third-party lib might raise
(including ones that might not inherit from Exception), it is not
possible to enumerate all of the possible exceptions so a bare
except: is the only reasonable option.

Change-Id: I4b44185df6b43316446b37225741523c7c829a3f

commit_message:
Change Network Topology panel so it stops polling ajax on error

Change javascript so that we don't use interval that will always call
AJAX, instead only schedule next AJAX poll when we have successfully
finished the previous AJAX request.
This avoids many calls with errors if token times out.

Fixes bug #1253768

Change-Id: I74c4bf8cb931655ce64783ae11467183275386ab

[{'created': '2013-12-03 08:38:29.000000000', 'message': "Docker Driver doesn't respect CPU limit

The docker driver doesn't respect the CPU settings of the configured
flavor.

Docker/LXC supports only relative cpu alloaction. The relative
cpu alloaction doesn't prevent that a container can use all CPUs but it
can at least insure that a container with more CPUs gets more CPU
cycles.

Change-Id: I3a28b5d99ac25fefc0502ace76d03bde0e3fed0d
Closes-Bug: #1256264
"}]
commit_message:
Docker Driver doesn't respect CPU limit

The docker driver doesn't respect the CPU settings of the configured
flavor.

Docker/LXC supports only relative cpu alloaction. The relative
cpu alloaction doesn't prevent that a container can use all CPUs but it
can at least insure that a container with more CPUs gets more CPU
cycles.

Change-Id: I3a28b5d99ac25fefc0502ace76d03bde0e3fed0d
Closes-Bug: #1256264

* Move MidonetInterfaceDriver to interface.py
* adapt interface driver midonet unit tests to mm-ctl

commit_message:
Fix "rename"/"snapshot-rename" command name

We can update the name and description of a volume using the command
"rename", so "rename" as the name of command is inappropriate.This patch
will modify "rename" to "update".

Also "snapshot-rename" will be modify to "snapshot-update".

Change-Id: I4ec940badc1008c6fb8ed1cbc452cc60bc2c8e9a
Closes-Bug: #1255847

commit_message:
Live migration support

Currently Horizon only provides support for 'nova migrate', which
involves a reboot, and is also confusing for users who do not know there
are 2 ways of migrating an instance. We should provide another option in
order to support live migration, as enabled by `nova live-migration`.

Implements blueprint live-migration-support

Change-Id: Id83ba9e19461a7217f521a09bde3109428ecbf11

commit_message:
Use assertAlmostEqual instead of failUnlessAlmostEqual in unit tests

The method failUnlessAlmostEqual has been deprecated since python 2.7.
http://docs.python.org/2/library/unittest.html#deprecated-aliases
Also in Python 3, a deprecated warning is raised when using
failUnlessAlmostEqual therefore we should use assertAlmostEqual instead.

Change-Id: Ic9947028afdb5b1ba8f19103018a6f1bc3fc551f
Closes-Bug: #1257068

"}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-11-25 15:29:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

+1 for moving the constraints to a separate file and re-using them for parameters.

-1 for combining the implementation of parameters and properties. They originally shared an implementation, but I split them up because they are essentially different things. We want to be able to add stuff to our own internal information about properties (update_allowed is the latest one) without it affecting the user-facing parameters. Also, properties and parameters have different types (e.g. CommaDelimitedList vs. List). They've already diverged and are evolving in different directions.

It may be possible to get them to share a superclass with some useful common functionality, but I don't think they should share the whole implementation. This would also solve the ugly import problem - there would be properties.Schema and parameters.Schema, each a subclass of schema.Schema, but only the properties and parameters modules would have to import the latter."}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2013-11-25 15:36:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the feedback, Zane. In fact my plan was not to have 100% code sharing between properties and parameters, but to have all the code that is common in one base class. For example, the constraints, the looping thru all constraints when validating etc. should be the same.

So my plan was to (1) factor out the current schema code into a separate file schema.py; (2) see what is properties specific and parameters specific to get a feeling for the common part --> introduce sub classes for PropertiesSchema and ParametersSchema.

I wanted to do part (1) in this patch as a first step and part (2) in a second patch (or maybe more patches) to not roll out everything at once.

Do you think this makes sense; is the commit message confusing?'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2013-11-25 15:41:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-25 16:45:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

one, common Schema class.

commit_message:
Factor Schema out of properties.py for re-use

There is currently some function duplication in Heat for schema
validation. There is properties.Schema and a ParamSchema class which
do mostly the same, but each with their own code.
It would be good to have a common implementation for property and
parameter validation with only property or parameter specific code
implemented in sub-classes.
The current Schema class in properties.py cannot be used in
parameters.py due to cyclic import dependencies that would arise.

This patch factors the Schema class and Constraint classes into their
own file which can then be imported by both properties.py and
parameters.py. For property schema specific code, a class
PropertySchema is introduced as derived from the common Schema class.

The code of the Schema and Constraint classes is unchanged except for
absolutely  refactoring work.

In a subsequent patch, I plan to provide the code to base ParamSchema
on the common Schema class.

Change-Id: I833edd8fad316220f56d6727fe1e3409f8fda6ee
Partial-Bug: #1230229

Fix adding router_id return attribute when CRU firewall and vip obj

    Work Done:
        1.adding router_id return attribute when CRU firewall/vip obj
        2.Adding router_id return attribute in unit test cases
        3.Adding list vip/firewall unit test cases
        4.Refactor duplicate codes
        5.Enhance Error Handle
        6.Add transparent mode in Neutron
        7.Add session_persistence implementation on Edge

Fixes Bug #1231770

Change-Id: I458b495d75904410d52663d22c782934144c5f61

commit_message:
Remove unused package in requirement.txt

This patch is similar to https://bugs.launchpad.net/glance/+bug/1252344.

Currently wsgiref/passlib package exist in requirement.txt,
but I confirmed that they are unused in glance source by "grep" command.

I removed them to clean up.

Closes-bug: #1255826
Change-Id: Ibbc2f1d413efacd0c18ba16c9250ef08470667d1

commit_message:
DB migration changes to support DB2 as sqlalchemy backend

Implements bp db2-database

SQLAlchemy works in general, only changes needed to allow DB2
backend are these migration updates. The main difference
with DB2 is around index creation and constraints updates.

Change-Id: If5aa371328ef49ec93029ed15993871cfe5522cd

commit_message:
Sync DB2 error code handling from oslo

Including DB2 error code -30081 in conn_err_codes, so that the
connection retry code will not be skipped when DB2 connection
error happens.

SHA1 of Oslo commit - bdabd512943ebb84a1333b2b3ee31a33124af76e to
which the db module code is syncd.

Change-Id: Idec7a6d712f5ed08fc0daad0a64df203c624f194
Closes-Bug: #1244092

So this is somewhat intentionally kept together because the function parameters of the available versions will change with sessions, and also it is actually more complicated than the regular client.Client situation, and i'm not sure yet how it will be used. 

Originally available_versions was public, it currently returns a dictionary of API version -> KeystoneVersion object. But i'm not sure if this is sufficient. What if there are two endpoints for a given API version - i don't know what that would mean anyway. How should you check if it's marked as stable? 

These are things that i think will become apparent, but can wait until someone asks us for them. 

As for how to read what is client and what is version discovery, the only thing that is specific to creating a Client object is done in the Client function. My only thought after reading through this is more of a NIT than anything else...perhaps we should expose a property on the Client factory to report "supported versions", looking to the future we will eventually move beyond v2 and v3.0 to other versions.  To be clear, this would be the versions supported by keystoneclient (not the server).

If you get an unsupported version error (or some such) but the only way to know that is to try discovery on something like v4.0, it seems like it is an unnessicary try/except where keystoneclient is consumed.  It could allow developers to pick a supported version (fall back) if suddenly they had an older version on their system.  Or just error without having to discover to know if the client could even support v<not 2 and not 3.0>.'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2013-10-23 22:31:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 20: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

So the generic client has two interfaces: 
 - discover: returns a dictionary keyed with version and value a dictionary containing url, id and stable.
 - discover_extensions: which won't work under v3 anyway, it requires you to provide it a v2 url. 

So given that it has the same arguments as a HTTPClient and then discards them it is essentially wrong and yes should be deprecated. 

I've been thinking more about it though. Do you think we should have a similar Discovery object that you call with 
discovery = keystoneclient.discover.Discover(url='http://localhost') 
and then you can query with discovery.get_client('v3.0') etc?

I didn't do it like this originally as the client.Client interface is dictated by a more global blueprint and this was all i was trying to support. commit_message:
Discover supported APIs

Allow discovery of the API versions a server supports and create an
appropriate client based on this.

Implements: blueprint api-version-discovery
Change-Id: I63e6759889066a784dc47e35152c82e1ead7951d

commit_message:
Use assertEqual instead of assertEquals in unit tests

The method assertEquals has been deprecated since python 2.7.
http://docs.python.org/2/library/unittest.html#deprecated-aliases
Also in Python 3, a deprecated warning is raised when using assertEquals
therefore we should use assertEqual instead.

Change-Id: Ic8f152766d70146300b74f3803d7dab1e4de50e2
Closes-Bug: #1256734

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-03 06:07:46.000000000', 'message': "Correct an inconsistency in KVS token backend

The KVS token backend was not enforcing that a token needed to be
associated to a specific user when listing tokens for trusts and
consumers.  Due to this oversight, the backend would allow the
test_auth.AuthWithTrust.assert_token_count_for_trust test to pass
incorrectly (working with trustee instead of trustor).

This fix needs to be in place prior to the KVS refactor as the new
key-value-store system does not give direct access to iterate over
the items in it's backing store since the backing store is not
guaranteed to be in process-memory (e.g. memcached vs in-memory dict).

bp: dogpile-kvs-backends
Change-Id: Iaf6b9343a37bd2d0622c2233f179bf01386dd4c5
"}]
commit_message:
Correct an inconsistency in KVS token backend

The KVS token backend was not enforcing that a token needed to be
associated to a specific user when listing tokens for trusts and
consumers.  Due to this oversight, the backend would allow the
test_auth.AuthWithTrust.assert_token_count_for_trust test to pass
incorrectly (working with trustee instead of trustor).

This fix needs to be in place prior to the KVS refactor as the new
key-value-store system does not give direct access to iterate over
the items in it's backing store since the backing store is not
guaranteed to be in process-memory (e.g. memcached vs in-memory dict).

bp: dogpile-kvs-backends
Change-Id: Iaf6b9343a37bd2d0622c2233f179bf01386dd4c5

Going to see if I can find a creative way around the rspec-puppet and ruby 1.8.7 hash ordering issue.'}, {'account_id': 8318, 'date': '2013-10-29 19:16:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 2265, 'date': '2013-10-29 19:22:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

one thing that comes to mind is that this patch actually does 3 things:

- decouple db migration from base configuration
- adds differentiation between public/admin/internal endpoints
- adds support for apache.

I would much rather see these things decoupled into 3 patches so that they can be validated separately. I think it's make the wsgi patch a lot easier to except if it is not touching the code classes.

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-23 19:23:32.000000000', 'message': "Enable serving keystone from apache mod_wsgi

Serving keystone from a wsgi container is recommended for production
setups. SSL is enabled by default.

See the following URLs for explanations:
    http://adam.younglogic.com/2012/03/keystone-should-move-to-apache-httpd/
    https://etherpad.openstack.org/havana-keystone-performance

Documentation in manifests/wsgi/apache.pp

Apache can be configured as a drop in replacement for keystone (using
    ports 5000 & 35357) or with paths using the standard SSL port. See
examples in examples/apache_*.pp

- Also change some 'real_' prefix into '_real' suffix to respect the
coding guide.
- Added the '--insecure' option to keystone client in the provider to
allow using self-signed certificates.
- Fixed parsing the ssl/enable value in the provider.

There is no integer verification done in the manifests
and to get around a bug in rspec, which has been fixed
in https://github.com/rodjek/rspec-puppet/pull/107,
certain parameters that should be integer are treated as
strings

Change-Id: Ide8c090d105c1ea75a14939f5e8ddb7d24ca3f1c

commit_message:
Enable serving keystone from apache mod_wsgi

Serving keystone from a wsgi container is recommended for production
setups. SSL is enabled by default.

See the following URLs for explanations:
    http://adam.younglogic.com/2012/03/keystone-should-move-to-apache-httpd/
    https://etherpad.openstack.org/havana-keystone-performance

Documentation in manifests/wsgi/apache.pp

Apache can be configured as a drop in replacement for keystone (using
    ports 5000 & 35357) or with paths using the standard SSL port. See
examples in examples/apache_*.pp

- Also change some 'real_' prefix into '_real' suffix to respect the
coding guide.
- Added the '--insecure' option to keystone client in the provider to
allow using self-signed certificates.
- Fixed parsing the ssl/enable value in the provider.

There is no integer verification done in the manifests
and to get around a bug in rspec, which has been fixed
in https://github.com/rodjek/rspec-puppet/pull/107,
certain parameters that should be integer are treated as
strings

files/httpd/keystone.py updated with lastest from keystone git repo

Change-Id: Ide8c090d105c1ea75a14939f5e8ddb7d24ca3f1c

commit_message:
Robustify determination of root directory

When tests are packaged into a different directory tree
than the nova module itself, traversing backwards to
the root directory does not work anymore with realpath/abspath.
Use normpath instead.

Closes-Bug: #1245553
Change-Id: Ifbc3947a03029dcd4c02b6498a8d48f7849b8f1a

commit_message:
Allow arbitrary provider templates for InstanceGroups

Add a property that allows the user to specify a provider template for an
InstanceGroup that can be used to scale nested stacks instead of only
Instances.

Change-Id: Ib179eab19c7db8a2280a54f5e9d708cff7282885

commit_message:
Implements volume backups via task flow

Implementing long-running operations via task flows is needed, so we can
better control the operation process. Task flows will eventually allow us
to pause/resume running backups, reverting in case of failure and
tracking progress of running tasks.

Implements: blueprint volume-backup-create-task-flow

Change-Id: Ia6c86b319e49d38bcf5be5d1b09eec4e08612f02

create an instance will return a default root password. We need to
display this password in a modal dialog to the end user. To achieve this
I add the screen to display default root password to the user with
copy-to-clipoard functionality.
If root_on_create is set to False in Trove.conf, orginal workflow is

Closes-Bug: #1254193
Change-Id: I5b7f8e67cbbedb89b27c6eb0ce339792e26fde4f
'}]
commit_message:
Add screen to display default root password

If root_on_create is set to True in Trove.conf, the api request to
create an instance will return a default root password. We need to
display this password in a modal dialog to the end user. To achieve this
I add the screen to display default root password to the user with
copy-to-clipoard functionality.
If root_on_create is set to False in Trove.conf, orginal workflow is
followed.

Closes-Bug: #1254193
Change-Id: I5b7f8e67cbbedb89b27c6eb0ce339792e26fde4f

commit_message:
Adds AvailabilityZone parameter to compute/notcompute templates

This is used to schedule the images to be launched onto specific
baremetal machines by Tuskar; the AvailabilityZoneFilter is used
to pass in az:node_uuid as per force_nodes extension that was
merged by Icfee63c80eb355c29594f8badde4183496b395ac

Change-Id: I0174d095b337f352350e059b8972b0dede96f088

commit_message:
GlusterFS: check whether share is writable before snapshotting

Test whether the share is writable before attempting to create or
delete a qcow2 snapshot.  This ensures that the entire snapshot
operation can be committed to disk rather than allowing the
snapshot info file and qcow2 data to get out of sync if part of
the operation fails due to the Cinder user not being able to write
to the directory.

Closes-Bug: #1236966

Change-Id: I975859699ea882110be6853a9ad6cd8c40253cc3

commit_message:
Create Router by Workflow

create router, set getway and set interface in a workflow.

implements bp create-router-by-workflow

commit_message:
LVM: remove size parameter from create_thin_pool()

This parameter is not used anywhere, and further requires the logic
implemented in _calculate_thin_pool_size() so it makes sense to remove
this as a parameter to create_thin_pool().

Change-Id: Ic76c5e23985236e51b25ea0d474016af4c3aa6b4

commit_message:
Add test for volume when creating a volume without display name

If we do not specify display_name, the volume should be created
successfully, and its name should be None.

Change-Id: I8a596b40a665c9261f14fc05e66afd830a89e784

commit_message:
Fix the problem that Scrubber tries to decrypt a decrypted uri.

Cleanup scrubber calls RegistryClient.get_images_detailed()
to get a list of pending_delete images, which contains
decrypted locations. However, the deletion method tries to
decrypt the locations again.

Fixes: bug #1193424
Change-Id: I1e29c4d6f5dfcaf70c7a7e3c871defd5c7e8d7c4

commit_message:
Store DIB_* only env variables

Or environment variables like OS_USERNAME OS_PASSWORD will be stored
in /etc/dib_environment also. It's potentially unsafe.

Change-Id: I3a65d5bc0e4469a071db9ac23ebc82196a3f3feb

I think we need a check (similar to what you removed) to see if anything was copied into the build root.  Just checking if any element was specified doesn't make sure at least one base element was added.

For instance, if you tried to build an image, and only specified "pip-cache", you get:

/home/jslagle/code/github/slagle/openstack/diskimage-builder $ bin/disk-image-create -o test pip-cache
Building elements: base  pip-cache
Expanded element dependencies to: pip-cache base
Building in /tmp/image.8QwmEO0j
dib-run-parts Wed Nov 27 07:43:13 EST 2013 Running /tmp/image.8QwmEO0j/hooks/root.d/01-ccache
dib-run-parts Wed Nov 27 07:43:13 EST 2013 01-ccache completed
dib-run-parts Wed Nov 27 07:43:13 EST 2013 Running /tmp/image.8QwmEO0j/hooks/root.d/01-pip-cache
dib-run-parts Wed Nov 27 07:43:13 EST 2013 01-pip-cache completed
----------------------- PROFILING -----------------------

Target: root.d

Script                                     Seconds
---------------------------------------  ----------

01-pip-cache                                  0.024
01-ccache                                     0.027

--------------------- END PROFILING ---------------------
touch: cannot touch '/tmp/image.8QwmEO0j/mnt/etc/resolv.conf': No such file or directory


If you're not super familiar with diskimage-builder, it may not be obvious what the problem was.  We could add back the check, and then if it fails, exit with a message similar to:

"It looks like nothing was copied into the build root, perhaps you forgot to specify a base element such as ubuntu or fedora".'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-11-27 19:19:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Drop default distribution root element support

Converts our existing default root element code to be just a check
which exits with a failure message if no root/distribution element
is found.

Change-Id: I954a6abfd7871d5807b1a171a03fa98932410cff

commit_message:
Fix show_deleted errors in RequestContext

get_admin_context takes a read_deleted argument which is ignored,
and we don't include the read_deleted value in to_dict output.
Fixing this means we can respect this flag in the DB API, which
currently we do not.

Change-Id: Id0906983b93cd2526580942390f7992fb2cb5504
blueprint: request-scoping-policy

commit_message:
Remove owner_is_tenant from RequestContext

This appears to be a leftover from glance, and we don't support
anything other than tenant-scoped requests.

Change-Id: Ibce0e38ee24f18de24733a35d25c90c03b46dc6e
blueprint: request-scoping-policy

commit_message:
Derive context is_admin from policy

Use a rule in the policy.json to correctly derive a user's admin-ness
based on their roles, when it is not explicitly specified in the
RequestContext constructor.

Keystone auth_token tests X-Roles based on the user role membership
for the tenant the token is scoped to, so this will allow us to define
per-tenant admins (the admin everywhere issue described in keystone
bug #968696 won't apply here, that is specific to keystone).

Remove the admin_role config option, which doensn't do anything, and
now this should be specified via policy.json.

Change-Id: I1921a2b515ecc8ca5d37205e3cdb6b7b8695b1ac
bluprint: request-scoping-policy

commit_message:
Use cleanup_flavor in setup-baremetal.

Adds an new cleanup_flavor function which we can use
to cleanup flavors a bit more nicely. This avoids
having setup-baremetal print out this nasty error
the first time it runs:

Change-Id: Ic237d4436b609a1ae08747a5b5d384b5da4909be
ERROR: No flavor with a name or ID of 'baremetal' exists.

commit_message:
Fix typo in keystoneclient

hypen-separated --> hyphen-separated
initialzied --> initialized
did't --> didn't
sematics --> semantics

Change-Id: I79841b76fdf7a267e325b8b9d917900ccb393c02
Closes-Bug: #1254660

commit_message:
Move flags in libvirt's volume to the libvirt group

This change continues moving libvirt specific flags into a libvirt
specific configuration group.

Progresses blueprint libvirt-opts-group.

DocImpact: the following flags have moved into the libvirt group:
    num_iscsi_scan_tries
    num_iser_scan_tries
    rbd_user
    rbd_secret_uuid
    nfs_mount_point_base
    nfs_mount_options
    num_aoe_discover_tries
    glusterfs_mount_point_base
    iscsi_use_multipath (formerly libvirt_iscsi_use_multipath)
    iser_use_multipath (formerly libvirt_iser_use_multipath)
    scality_sofs_config
    scality_sofs_mount_point
    qemu_allowed_storage_drivers

Change-Id: I78941aff4bf49fc70d91a3239deff44dbaaab6c9

commit_message:
Convert revocation list file last modified to UTC

On a restart of a service using auth_token middleware, the last modified
time of the revocation list file is checked to decide whether to get the
fresh list from keystone. In server timezones that are ahead of UTC,
this compares a local time with UTC. This means whenever a service is
restarted it doesn't update the revocation list for the length of the
timezone offset from UTC.

This change converts the last modified time to UTC when it's first
read, so the comparison is valid.

Closes-bug: 1204000
Change-Id: I623b6273beb56f8da2a8649a10a64318da8cd6bc

commit_message:
Show success msg when container deletion succeeds

When user tries to delete non-empty container, the success messsage
should not be displayed.

Change-Id: I02ba1e4bad8dbe2b52f06f2a8e079b5812cd5544
Closes-bug: 1214842

We add the "log_accurate" boolean option for the proxy-logging
middleware, which when True, will use the timestamps for the start and
end times for a request. The current default of using a datetime
formatted value is field 2 ("01/Jan/1970/00/00/01") and a relative
request duration time in seconds (floating point) is preserved.

The goal is to allow for log processing that can use the more accurate
timestamps to correlate requests, computing number of requests in
flight at a given historical point in time.

commit_message:
Add accurate timestamps in proxy log

Add accurate timestamps to the proxy-logging middleware log lines for
the start and end of a request. We use 9 digits of precision since on
some systems the clock resolution can be as fine as 1 ns.

The goal is to allow for log processing that can use the more accurate
timestamps to correlate requests, computing number of requests in
flight at a given historical point in time.

Change-Id: I61e8784b1c455d629f1299207fc4fc7e4a134814
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Add heatclient to available clients

The first resource to use this will need to ensure
that this method has test coverage. There appears to be
no convention for writing separate unit tests for these
client methods.

This will currently not work with standalone heat as
the heat endpoint will not be in the keystone catalog, see
related-bug: #1255713

partial blueprint: hot-software-config
Change-Id: I325664dcb0ca4d01be41614496c92e65bea52310

commit_message:
Replace removed xrange in Python3

Built-in function xrange were used in Python 2 were removed in
Python3. Python3 uses range, we use range() to support both
Python2 and Python3.

Change-Id: Ib4e4f833866ed6653f75e0ace67f1d9fa493babf
Closes-bug: #1256159

commit_message:
Allow Pecan to use 'debuginfo' response field

Currently we have Pecan app improperly integrated with WSME, api
config does not include 'wsme' section. Therefore 'debuginfo'
response field intended to carry exception traceback when server
in debug mode is never used. This patch adds wsme section to api
config with debug field picked from ironic.conf.
This patch also adds documentation references for existing configs.

Change-Id: Iabc042a533c0e3357853a01267ea2252bd61e6e1
Closes-Bug: #1254002

Generally it's ok, just I would like to see more consistency across your change:

- you used explicitly _nova/_neutron method calls there, so I seems better to remove that 'magic' part (isinstance... checks) from upper part of manager and change all places to call explicit version (or are there places which we really want to 'switchable' between those two?)

- also in some places you don't provide client arg, but in some places you do, from already set local 'client' var, or as self.network_client - which seems quite redundant as it would have used self.network_client there anyway

- also (if it won't be removed as i pointed that possibility above) in those methods with isinstance checks, in one you default to _nova if client is not network_client, but in the other method you raise ValueError if it's not explicitly nova_cl or network_cl ... and I would expect same default behavior from both

commit_message:
Support Neutron security groups in scenario testing

The methods
NetworkScenarioTest._create_security_group()
and
NetworkScenarioTest.create_loginable_secgroup_rule()
use the nova client by default.

Added helper functions "*_neutron" that use the neutron (network)
client.
Moved old implementation into "*_nova" for old usage.

Adds methods to scenario/manager to allow for generic creation of
neutron secgroup and rules as existing methods only create a secgroup
with login rules (incoming ping and ssh).

Change-Id: I6de4bf9f7deed215cf61c87c3ae3f4240982523e

commit_message:
Add flavor-extra-specs to core for V3 API

Adds the flavor-extra-specs plugin to the core list for the V3 API.
This is part of the process of adding all of the flavor related
extensions to core, with the exception of rxtx, as per the discussion
here: https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/NovaV3APICore

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: Id4b4fad5e584bdf2bbbaaae579a07e28c312ef34

subject: Add flavor-access to core for V3 API

commit_message:
Add flavor-access to core for V3 API

Adds the flavor-access plugin to the core list for the V3 API.
This is part of the process of adding all of the flavor related
extensions to core, with the exception of rxtx, as per the discussion
here: https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/NovaV3APICore

Note that since the alias changes from os-flavor-access to flavor-access
the api samples move directory and quite a few of other api samples
as well as flavor access is included by default.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

DocImpact

Change-Id: I9abc7df8f4620d462b0d381a2c0ed180c48f220e

commit_message:
Remove kernel-headers apt-get call

Kernel-headers is no longer necessary since it's
installed by devstack_gate.sh script. This will
also add support to Fedora and other distros
once apt-get isn't being called anymore.

Change-Id: I36b9a126a62a0c80562b0c22a94af3ce08a9008e

commit_message:
docker: access system_metadata as a dict

This bit of code causes a problem when moving to objects.  The Instance
object presents system_metadata as you would normally expect (a dict).
The data is in a different format when working with a db instance.  Use
the handy helper utility to normalize it into a dict.

Change-Id: Ieca9ab449a07374ed2c9cdaffdfd54783df7a866

'}, {'account_id': 1882, 'date': '2013-10-28 14:06:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 18.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-10-28 14:25:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 18: Do not merge

(2 inline comments)

I think this is a bad idea for several reasons, including:

1. It introduces FOUR additional RPC round-trips to conductor, along with four hits to the database on almost every call into  manager. That's an incredibly large amount of additional traffic, especially when we already have a copy of the instance.

2. It breaks ownership of the task_state, which today is almost entirely that the API owns setting (and reading) task_state and the manager owns unsetting (i.e. setting it to None) when an operation is complete. We already have a mechanism to ensure that task_state=None on errors.

3. I think that on restart of nova-compute, if the instance is still assigned to us, and its state is BUILDING, then we should be able to set it to error in _init_instance() and move on."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-28 14:37:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: Works for me

Hey Dan,

This would only ever be setting task_state to None it would not be overriding the APIs function in that regard. However it would  handle more than just the situation where something is in error state. There are many states currently that would not progress if a compute manager failed/restarted during their operations but the instance they relate to would still be either recoverable or fully functional, this would identify some of these states and transition them to None along with a vm_state that is more useful to the user.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-10-28 16:40:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: (1 inline comment)

For long-running things that we need to be able to recover from, I think the accepted goal is to make conductor track and push those.'}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2013-10-29 14:31:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18:

Hi Dan,

>1. It introduces FOUR additional RPC round-trips to conductor, along with four hits to the database on almost every call into manager. That's an incredibly large amount of additional traffic, especially when we already have a copy of the instance.

Agree that's something that needs to be looked at - I think that was only introduced because one reviewer said that not all calls got an Instance object.   Some additional task states to disambiguate when a message has been received and started procession on the compute manager could also avoid some or all of this.   

>2. It breaks ownership of the task_state, which today is almost entirely that the API owns setting (and reading) task_state and the manager owns unsetting (i.e. setting it to None) when an operation is complete. We already have a mechanism to ensure that task_state=None on errors.

That's really only true for the very simple operations;  Build/rebuilt/shelve/migrate/snapshot go through a number of task state transitions within the compute manager. 


>3. I think that on restart of nova-compute, if the instance is still assigned to us, and its state is BUILDING, then we should be able to set it to error in _init_instance() and move on.

Building is only once case we've found that needs to be cleaned up - and even here you need some way to distinguish between "Building" because the request was running on the compute manager, and "Building" because it's in transit from the scheduler to the compute manager. 

>For long-running things that we need to be able to recover from, I think the accepted goal is to make conductor track and push those.
As far as I know there isn't yet a design that shows how conductor would be able to be 100% sure that a thread in the compute manager is no longer running, which is why doing cleanup at as part of the compute-manager start-up (the one time that you do know there are no in-flight operations) seems like a good approach.   There is already some clean-up performed - this extends that approach and make it more robust.

There has also been an accepted goal since at least Folsom that we would get a clean shut-down of the compute manager so that we don't get these kind interrupted task states in the manager, but it hasn't landed yet.   Whatever the long term goals are it doesn't to me always follow that we can't make incremental improvements ahaed of those changes.


Maybe this would be a good unconference session next week ?'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-10-29 19:52:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18:

Sure, sounds good.'}, {'account_id': 1882, 'date': '2013-10-30 14:49:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 18:

In light of the recent comments I'm going to scale back this change to deal with the task states related to BUILDING (as outlined in Bug 1197024).

Also I think there will still be some states which we could be cleaning up on start-up without the need of adding the overhead of the DB hits but I think I will suggest those in a separate change."}, {'account_id': 1882, 'date': '2013-10-31 16:57:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 19.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-31 17:36:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 19: Doesn't seem to work

[{'created': '2013-09-23 13:42:06.000000000', 'message': 'Recover from transient state on compute manager start-up

If a compute manager is stopped / fails during a certain
operations then the instance will be left stuck in a transient
vm_state or task_state.

During the restart of the compute service there are a number of
these states which we can be sure are no longer accurate and as
such we can switch these instances to a more consistent state.

For example, as outlined in bug 1197024, an instance in the BUILDING
state on start-up can be set to ERROR as the thread building this
particular instance will have been lost when the compute manager
stopped.

bug 1197024

commit_message:
Recover from build state on compute manager start-up

If a compute manager is stopped / fails during a build operation
then the instance will be left stuck with vm_state=BUILDING

During restart the one thing we can be sure about such instances
is that providing the task state is not SCHEDULING (i.e the request
is not still on the queue) then there is no thread running for this
instance.

In this case we can treat instances in this state as if they have
failed to spawn and put the into an ERROR state.

Closes-Bug: 1197024
Related to blueprint recover-stuck-state

Change-Id: I7b116d8154036c43b0feb23f5669f52358408d2b

commit_message:
Provide access to Trove client

python-troveclient is required for implementing Database As A
Service (DBaaS) resource. This patch makes Heat depend on
python-troveclient and also changing clients.py and resource.py
to provide access to troveclient.

Implements: blueprint dbaas-trove-resource

Change-Id: I010d4a11793cc634aa0af5f01b637fff4effbf61

[{'created': '2013-12-02 21:18:38.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Return a descriptive error message for controllers"

This reverts commit 6512c71a49c14e1a2f7a857a37b96883def57788.

While this fixes the problem it doesn't do it in a comprehensive way.
The right way would be to implement real validation.

The reverted patch breaks on methods marked as deprecated because the
deprecated decorator is a function that accepts *args and **kwargs.
This bypasses the check and we go back to the same TypeError from the
original bug.

Change-Id: I0efbcce9abc23bf79eb970e441e5f7644b1c8453
'}, {'created': '2013-12-02 21:19:42.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Return a descriptive error message for controllers"

This reverts commit 6512c71a49c14e1a2f7a857a37b96883def57788.

While this fixes the problem it doesn't do it in a comprehensive way.
The right way would be to implement real validation.

The reverted patch breaks on methods marked as deprecated because the
deprecated decorator is a function that accepts *args and **kwargs.
This bypasses the check and we go back to the same TypeError from the
original bug.

Related-Bug: #1149987

commit_message:
Revert "Return a descriptive error message for controllers"

This reverts commit 6512c71a49c14e1a2f7a857a37b96883def57788.

While this fixes the problem it doesn't do it in a comprehensive way.
The right way would be to implement real validation.

The reverted patch breaks on methods marked as deprecated because the
deprecated decorator is a function that accepts *args and **kwargs.
This bypasses the check and we go back to the same TypeError from the
original bug.

Related-Bug: #1149987
Change-Id: I0efbcce9abc23bf79eb970e441e5f7644b1c8453

commit_message:
Update openstack/common/lockutils

The following commits are in this update:

79e6bc6 fix lockutils.lock() to make it thread-safe
ace5120 Add main() to lockutils that creates temp dir for locks
537d8e2 Allow lockutils to get lock_path conf from envvar
371fa42 Move LockFixture into a fixtures module
d498c42 Fix to properly log when we release a semaphore

Change-Id: Iefe5f90b3886c58736bdb27e9019bc19a8e49179

commit_message:
Remove V2 API version of coverage extensions

As discussed at the summit in the QA stream, this removes
the coverage extension from the V2 API.

According to the API Change Guidelines
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/APIChangeGuidelines
we should not be doing this. However the coverage
extension is a rather special case. It has security issues
such that it shouldn't be used in a production cloud
environment. It also doesn't work properly so its usefulness
to measure API coverage is limited. And in the past the presence of
this plugin has been used as a reason not to accept
an alternative technique to measure API coverage.

This is the proposed replacement

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/25882/

Change-Id: I07d798129ee277a6f7691c25f88c07a5204c0943

commit_message:
Remove V3 API version of coverage extension

As discussed at the summit in the QA session, this removes
the coverage extension from the V3 API. The coverage extension
doesn't work properly and has security issues. An alternative technique,
though more limited in nature will soon be proposed.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: Ib4296288fefeb7e1e11bb6e44bd1cf355f29b9b9

[{'created': '2013-11-14 06:07:38.000000000', 'message': 'Enable a uuid flavor

Current tempest configuration enforces a flavor id should be integer,
but we can create a uuid flavor. For example, the following command
creates a flavor with auto-generated uuid:

  $ nova flavor-create m3.small auto 512 0 1

This patch enables a uuid flavor by changing flavor_id type from integer
to string.

Change-Id: I6567ef3086710508ef4215e93634601119ce3402

commit_message:
Enable a uuid flavor

Current tempest configuration enforces a flavor id should be integer,
but we can create a uuid flavor. For example, the following command
creates a flavor with auto-generated uuid:

  $ nova flavor-create m3.small auto 512 0 1

This patch enables a uuid flavor by changing a flavor_id type from
integer to string.

Change-Id: I6567ef3086710508ef4215e93634601119ce3402

commit_message:
Expose bulk-operation limits in /info.

These will allow clients to perform the minimal number of requests
required to accomplish some bulk tasks. For example, a client with
many objects to delete can learn that the cluster's limit on
deletes-per-request is, say, 128, and then batch up their deletes in
groups of 128. Without this, the client has to either discover the
limit out-of-band somehow (and get notified if it changes), or do some
sort of binary search to figure out the limit.

Similar reasoning applies to the containers-per-request value.

The errors-per-request values are included so that clients may size
their requests such that everything is attempted regardless of
failure.

I split the 'bulk' entry into 'bulk_delete' and 'bulk_upload' because,
from a client's standpoint, they're separate operations. It so happens
that Swift implements both in one piece of middleware, but clients
don't care.

Bonus fix: documented a missing config setting for the bulk middleware.

Change-Id: Ic3549aef79682fd5b798145c3545c1609aa1592b

https://github.com/openstack/horizon/blob/master/openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/projects/views.py#L84"}, {'account_id': 4978, 'date': '2013-11-29 17:08:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

Hi,

Thank you for your contribution. You have 2 reviews opened for the same bug (this and https://review.openstack.org/#/c/58928/ ), that touch different files. Are they related? If so they should be marked dependent or merged into one. If not, one should be abandoned.

I don't think this is the right approach, as this assumes we have received all the data already, which is rarely the case and inefficient (there can be 1,000s of objects). That's why we normally use the APIs to paginate (with the current restrictions this entails). With the Django pagination we end up requesting the full dataset each page rather than only what we want to display, which is not desirable.

As it is, it also conflicts with the current pagination since they're both there. For example if I look at the list of instances, I now see both the API pagination (displaying 10 items, More >>) + the django pagination (1 | 2). And if I start e.g. 25 instances with the default settings (20 items per pages) the conflict becomes more obvious, as the django pagination disappears when we get to the last page clicking More."}, {'account_id': 6704, 'date': '2013-12-03 01:16:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Abandoned

replaced  by another change set'}, {'account_id': 6704, 'date': '2013-12-03 01:33:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I should abandoned this change set early.

The other change set (58928) is a replacement to this change set. It uses existing pagination instead of creating the new one.

However, there are lots of problems in using current pagination from API:
1. it can not display correct pagination if the API result is filtered, eg:
 https://review.openstack.org/#/c/58928/1/openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/images_and_snapshots/views.py 

2. it can hardly deal with ResourceBrowser type of views, like the view used for "Containers" and "Objects"

3. the "more" button should append next page to current tables, but it actually replace current page to next page, which is hard to navigate between lots of pages.

I'd like the next version of APIs to return a django paginator like of object instead of using the last item to display next page.'}]

I'm surprised this helps and need some time to experiment w/this patch.  Will try to do that ASAP."}, {'account_id': 5499, 'date': '2013-07-12 19:48:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

So here are the actual numbers. I made three transactions:

1/ swift command with pre-auth information:

sudo swift --os-auth-token=abcdef --os-storage-url=https://storage-url/123456 download swift-client-container object
object [headers 0.020s, total 0.020s, 0.506s MB/s]


2/ swift command WITHOUT pre-auth information:

sudo swift -A https://auth-url/v1.0 -U 123456:user -K **** download swift-client-container object
object [headers 0.059s, total 0.059s, 0.174s MB/s]

which turned out to be significantly slower. The reason for that was that Connection object passed into download function was created with authentication details. Time measured for the headers included authentication time from swift client library. This change improves this logic in the way that it authenticates BEFORE passing the Connection object to download function where time starts being measured. The object passed into the function is not containing authentication details any more, but pre-auth information, which allows client library to skip authentication.

Below are results after the improvement:

sudo swift -A https://auth-url/v1.0 -U 123456:user -K **** download swift-client-container object
object [headers 0.020s, total 0.020s, 0.515s MB/s]'}, {'account_id': 2696, 'date': '2013-07-12 21:15:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

The pre-auth seems reasonable on its own.

However, if you're concerned about the accuracy of the average per-request throughput reported in the output being affected by latency induced by authentication inside the Connection instance, it seems that should be addressed by removing the authentication latency from the reported time-to-first-byte and total time in the library call.  In other words, you've tried to address the accuracy in bin/swift's usage of swiftclient.client, but not helped other users of the library.

The "auth" command is unnecessary, as "stat -v" already returns that information.'}, {'account_id': 860, 'date': '2013-07-15 18:33:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: No score

I didn't know -v printed that info -- good to know.

Wrt to this change only affecting the performance metric numbers, this is not true. When uploading or downloading a container (lots of objects), you only need to authenticate once. On a transatlantic hop, this should be noticeable."}, {'account_id': 2696, 'date': '2013-07-15 20:10:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I implemented a transatlantic authentication (see patch below).  The below downloads were of a container with 41 objects.

master code, with 1s sleep in authentication:

  real	0m3.912s
  user	0m0.223s
  sys	0m0.117s

  real	0m3.646s
  user	0m0.219s
  sys	0m0.117s

  real	0m3.617s
  user	0m0.213s
  sys	0m0.106s

  AVG real:  3.725s

With HEAD is now at b312fde... Add pre-authentication in swift command.

  real	0m3.287s
  user	0m0.236s
  sys	0m0.163s

  real	0m3.168s
  user	0m0.227s
  sys	0m0.158s

  real	0m3.185s
  user	0m0.228s
  sys	0m0.150s

  AVG real: 3.213s
  Delta (from without patch):  0.512s   (51.2% of the introduced authentication latency of 1s, and clearly not much of a function of the number of files downloaded)

With HEAD is now at b312fde... Add pre-authentication in swift command. and normally-fast authentication:

  real	0m1.329s
  user	0m0.230s
  sys	0m0.161s

  real	0m1.299s
  user	0m0.278s
  sys	0m0.166s

  AVG real: 1.314
  Delta (from with-patch, 1s delay): 1.899s (189% of the introduced latency of 1s)

I guess the ConnectonPool has to warm up, authenticating each connection or something... but that's clearly done concurrently.  The overall improvement of the patch on wall-time (with slow authentication) is low: just over 50% of the introduced authentication latency.  OTOH, not introducing a 1s delay in authentication drops the wall-time by 189% of the introduced delay.  So I think the moral of the story, here, is that the most bang-for-your-buck will come from reducing the time an authentication takes.

Also, note that the "pain" of a slow authentication does NOT seem to scale with the number of objects in the container being downloaded.  Did you run some tests which exhibited that behavior?

Slow-auth patch:

  diff --git a/swiftclient/client.py b/swiftclient/client.py
  index e95819f..236f899 100644
  --- a/swiftclient/client.py
  +++ b/swiftclient/client.py
  @@ -287,6 +287,7 @@ def get_auth(auth_url, user, key, **kwargs):
       use of this network path causes no bandwidth charges but requires the
       client to be running on Rackspace's ServiceNet network.
       """
  +    sleep(1)  # transatlantic authentication in the house!
       auth_version = kwargs.get('auth_version', '1')

[{'created': '2013-07-03 15:25:50.000000000', 'message': "Add pre-authentication in swift command.

We noticed a difference in download bandwidth while using
authentication details and pre-auth information for download.
Download using authentication details included authentication
time into the download bandwidth at each call of the function.
This time should have been excluded from download bandwidth.

This patch set is fixing the problem by authenticating only
once - before Connection object is used anywhere further - and
then overriding Connection object's parameters with the new
pre-auth information. Then whenever Connection is used,
authentication steps are omitted.

The fix generally improves performance by decreasing number of
calls into the get_auth function as well as fixes the command
to report correct bandwidth.

For convenience reasons also added auth command in case user
wants to obtain auth token and storage url using only the swift
tool.

Change-Id: I63df9023e169f637f120ae9e25dac9c90a4e75a0
Fixes: bug #1197443

commit_message:
Fix download bandwidth for swift command.

We noticed a difference in download bandwidth while using
authentication details and pre-auth information for download.
Download using authentication details included authentication
time into the download bandwidth at each call of the function.
This time should have been excluded from download bandwidth.

This patch set is adding a timer variable to the client library.
That allows to accurately measure and store the time of each action.
Then while printing the download bandwith in the swift command
authentication time is excluded from bandwidth.

Change-Id: I63df9023e169f637f120ae9e25dac9c90a4e75a0
Fixes: bug #1197443

commit_message:
keystoneclient requires an email address when creating a user

python-keystoneclient v2.0 currently requires an email address,
but Keystone doesn't require an email address any longer.

Closes-Bug: #1252621
Change-Id: I4fe54aca9efcb0e5ab6ad901ee94796a04035224

commit_message:
Warn user about unsupported API version

Prints a warning when the user tries to use an unsupported API.
Also provides a test case to check it still does fall back to 2.0.

Change-Id: Idabd150f52d27a9d065cf570f6367459126f98be
Closes-bug: #1256987
